				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Spain&#8217;s King Juan Carlos abdicated his throne in June, he received resounding praise for his leadership through the country&#8217;s troubled transition to democracy in the 20th century. But many critics in constitutional monarchies throughout the world continue to ask the question: Is the tradition of royalty too luxurious and costly to maintain?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Spain, Carlos&#8217;s popular move did not change the fact that its economy is still wobbly in the wake of the Great Recession. Ordinary Spaniards <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/04/world/europe/spain-abdication.html">are questioning the preservation</a> of a royal family that receives an annual budget of 7.8 million euros (about $11 million).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And a spate of tabloid-worthy scandals in recent years did not aid the royalist cause.Â âNothing has been the same since the day, two years ago, when King Juan Carlos was revealed to have broken his hip on an elephant-hunting trip to Botswana, and was flown home to be treated at an exclusive clinic,&#8221;Â <a href="//www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2014/06/the-fall-of-king-juan-carlos-spains-monarch-abdicates.html">writes</a>Â Jon Lee Anderson for The New Yorker. &#8220;That the King was clueless enough to kill elephants for sport is embarrassing. (Who does that nowadays?) The news that the junket, complete with private jet, had been subsidized by a Syrian-born Saudi businessman was also unpleasant. Then it emerged that the King had been on the trip with a woman who was not Queen Sofia, and the Spanish press reported that the woman, a German aristocrat, was his mistress.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This incident followed an investigation into whether Juan Carlos&#8217;s son-in-law, IÃ±aki Urdangarin, the husband of Princess Cristina, had &#8220;taken funds from the 6 million euros his nonprofit foundation received from regional governments in Valencia and the Balearic Islands for organizing events such as sports seminars.&#8221;Â <a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/29/spain-europe-news?guni=Article:in%20body%20link">According to The Guardian</a>, the claims state that he diverted funds to for-profit companies under his direction.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All in all, it seems the time was ripe for a royal change of hands in Spain. The new king, Felipe, enjoys a favorable reputation among Spaniards. The AFP <a href="//www.thelocal.es/20140619/king-felipe-spain-crowds-enthronement-crown">reports</a>Â âa poll taken after Juan Carlos announced his abdication to aÂ surprised nation on June 2 showed almost 77 percent of respondents had a goodÂ or very good opinion of his son.&#8221; And while <a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/08/spain-majority-referendum-monarchy">62 percent of Spaniards believe</a> there should be a referendum on whether to maintain monarchy, overall, <a href="//www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/60b91a3e-f6f2-11e3-b271-00144feabdc0.html?siteedition=intl#slide0">53 percent say they want to keep it</a>, with only 37 percent favoring a republic.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This appears to be a theme common to monarchies worldwide. Even in Australia, where the idea of sloughing off commonwealth status and accompanying Windsor affiliations has been percolating for decades, only 39 percent of voters today support a shift to republicanismÂ â &#8220;<a href="//www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/republican-cause-takes-heavy-knock-in-poll-20140201-31u1a.html">a 20-year low</a>,&#8221; according to Bianca Hall of The Sydney Morning Herald.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Back in Spain, royalist sentiments appear similarly battered, yet steadfast: &#8220;The question is whether Spanish youth will be content with a younger, more popular, less scandal-tainted king, or whether they will demand significant changes to the monarchy orÂ <a href="//online.wsj.com/articles/king-juan-carlos-abdication-leads-to-debate-on-spanish-monarchy-1401730150">even its outright abolition</a>,&#8221; <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/06/will-spanish-youth-tolerate-another-king-of-spain/372027/">writes</a> Uri Friedman for The Atlantic. âAnÂ <a href="//elpais.com/elpais/2014/05/03/media/1399138904_941820.html">El PaÃ­sÂ survey</a>Â in May indicated that 64 percent of 18- to 34-year-olds agreed that Spain&#8217;s transition to democracy wouldn&#8217;t have been possible without Juan Carlos, and that the crown is firmly established in the country.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Celebrity appeal <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/04/30/world/europe/30britain.html?pagewanted=all">has bolstered Britain&#8217;s monarchy</a> with the marriage (<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/07/25/world/europe/and-the-name-isgeorge-alexander-louis.html">and subsequent propagation</a>) of the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge. And it appears Spain has its own answer to Kate Middleton in the newly crowned Queen Letizia, a former newscaster.Â âLetizia represents a new, more progressive era for the royals,&#8221; <a href="//www.independent.ie/irish-news/news/fixing-the-familys-image-from-within-30374003.html">writes</a>Â The Irish Independent&#8217;s Julia Molony. &#8220;She is impeccably photogenic and has perfect poise. More than just media-friendly, she is a media professional, and will understand how to control and manage her family&#8217;s image. Most importantly, like Kate Middleton, she brings two vital qualities to her new role â great hair and a spine of steel.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Perhaps this combination of history, sentimentality and fresh glamor will preserve the House of Bourbon. The hand-off of the crown to a figure with decidedly more public trust certainly comes at a crucial economic and political moment in Spain. <a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/17/spain-king-catalan-independence-artur-mas">According to The Guardian</a>, &#8220;recent European election results point to growing support for independence in Catalonia,&#8221; Spain&#8217;s prosperous autonomous region in the northeast, the secession of which would be <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2012/11/21/why-catalonia-probably-wont-secede-from-spain/">a devastating blow</a> to the already limping Spanish economy. As of 2012, Catalonia composed &#8220;20 percent of Spain&#8217;s economy,&#8221; and its per-capita G.D.P. was &#8220;one-fifth higher than the rest of Spain,&#8221; according to The Washington Post&#8217;s Blad Plumer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Many Spaniards are looking to Felipe to maintain a united Spain, much in the way his father presided over the uncertain times after Franco&#8217;s death. An injection of new blood seems de rigueur for a number of the world&#8217;s courtly institutions: Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands <a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2013/apr/30/queen-beatrix-abdicates-dutch-throne-to-crown-prince-willem-alexander-live-coverage">replacing Queen Beatrix</a> as well as Albert II of Belgium <a href="//www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/10158189/Belgiums-King-Albert-abdicates-on-grounds-of-ill-health.html">abdicating to his son</a>, Philippe, not to mention Pope Benedict XVI&#8217;s resignation from office last year âÂ the first papal abdication since 1415 â which made way for Francis.Â As Jon Lee Anderson puts it, &#8220;Just as Pope Francisâs populist measures may well save the Catholic Church, replacing Juan Carlos may save the Spanish monarchy.&#8221; And quite possibly the Spanish state itself.</p>
	</div>
